<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-320-636  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 320 636.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 5 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>International investigation nets three Australian hackers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zucker, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryAustraliaComputer CrimesLegal IssuesComputer hackersCourt Cases.andO;Person:    Jones, Richard Martin (cases); Evan-Chaim, Nashon (cases);Woodcock, David John (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INTERNATIONAL INVESTIGATION NETS THREE AUSTRALIAN HACKERS MELBOURNE,AUSTRALIA, 1990 APRIL 2 (NB) -- Three Australian computer hackers have beenarrested in Melbourne following a long investigation involving US andAustralian police and security organizations.andM;Richard Martin Jones, 20, was charged on 14 counts relating to illegal accessto computers using Australian Commonwealth facilities (the telephone system).andO;Nashon Evan-Chaim, 18, was charged with six similar counts and David JohnWoodcock was charged on two counts.andP;  All three are out on bail pending theircourt appearance scheduled for May 3.andM;The charges were made by Australian federal police who had been investigatingthe Australian end of numerous instances of hackers illegally entering UScomputer and communication systems.andM;The relevant section of the Australian crimes act, instituted just last year,allows a maximum penalty of up to ten years imprisonment for &quot;damaging datain Commonwealth and other computers by means of a Commonwealth facility.&quot;andO;There is no provision for a fine.andM;During the course of the arrests, a quantity of computer equipment,print-outs and software was confiscated.andP;  The arrests were made early in themorning, and all computers were disabled quickly to prevent the destructionof evidence.andM;One of those arrested is believed to be the person who recently soughtpublicity by contacting US newspapers to boast of his endeavors.andP;  He isaccused of causing malicious damage to files and computer systems includingthose of NASA and Citibank.andM;(Paul Zucker/19900404/Press Contact: Australian Federal Police.andP;  KeithLivingston ph.andP;  +61-3-6077307)</TEXT></DOC>